article.headline: Minnesota's Big 3 lead the way
article.linkText: Timberwolves defend turf by routing Blazers
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Latrell Sprewell and the Minnesota Timberwolves beat Portland Thursday night, before the Trail Blazers even woke up. Sprewell scored 25 points, including 19 in the first half, to lead Minnesota over the travel weary Blazers 96-75. "We got going early and I don't think there's any secret to that," Sprewell said. "We did a great job of attacking and getting transition baskets." Kevin Garnett had 26 points and 14 rebounds and Sam Cassell added 10 points and 11 assists for Minnesota, which has won 14 of 17 and seven straight at home. The Wolves opened the game with a 15-2 run while Portland missed eight of its first nine shots. Minnesota never looked back. "We want to come out hard and make a statement early to whoever we're playing," said Cassell. "We'll start it out there and figure everything else out over the course of the rest of the game." Zach Randolph scored 19 points for the Blazers, who did not arrive in Minneapolis until 3:15 a.m. due to hazardous weather conditions in Portland. "I think a lot of it is that they got in late," Sprewell said. "It's always tough to play when you don't have rest." That lack of rest translated into 41-percent shooting and 16 turnovers, as the Blazers fell to 1-13 on the road. "We can't make excuses, they just took it to us," said Jeff McInnis, who scored 15 points. "You just have to play for pride, give it effort. I don't feel like we did that tonight." The poor weather in the Pacific Northwest, which forced the game against Memphis on Tuesday to be postponed, also prevented center Dale Davis from flying out to Minneapolis. "Mother nature works in strange ways," Cassell said. "It's part of the NBA," said Portland coach Maurice Cheeks. Davis' absence, combined with early foul trouble for Rasheed Wallace, allowed Garnett and Sprewell to drive the lane with ease throughout the game. Minnesota finished with a 42-30 advantage for points in the paint. "There's no remedy for being tired, that's our job and we have to do it," Cheeks said. "Nobody feels sorry for us." Wallace was held to just eight points and two rebounds in 26 minutes,in Portland's fourth straight loss. Wallace picked up his second foul at the 8:06 mark of the first quarter and sat for most of the half as Minnesota continued to dominate the Blazers. Garnett and Sprewell combined for 33 points in the half and the Wolves shot 57.5 percent from the field to go into the break up 55-33. The Wolves extended their lead to 65-40 with 7:23 left in the third. The closest Portland got in the second half was 75-58 at end of third. Minnesota's Oliver Miller had eight points and seven rebounds. Portland's Qyntel Woods had 10 points and eight rebounds. Game notes
Minnesota forward Gary Trent sprained his right ankle in warmups and played 10 minutes in the first half, but he did not come out for the second. According to coach Flip Saunders, Trent hurt himself when he landed on a ball. He is day-to-day. ... Cassell has nine point-assist double-doubles. ... Davis, who lives in the west hills of Portland, was unable to meet a late-night team bus to the Eugene airport -- a move that became necessary when Portland International Airport was closed. ... Both Portland's 15 points in the first quarter, and 33 in the first half, were season lows. ... The Blazers stopped Minnesota's season-high six-game winning streak on Dec. 26 in Portland, 101-92.
